Generics in Java

Generics in Java allow us to write flexible and reusable code by using types as parameters.

Instead of working with a specific type (like String or Integer), we can write code that works with any type, while still keeping type safety.

Why Generics are useful

Before generics, collections (like ArrayList) stored objects as Object.
This caused two main problems:

we had to cast manually
errors could appear at runtime

Generics solve this by providing compile-time type checking.

Example without Generics
ArrayList list = new ArrayList();
list.add("Hello");

String text = (String) list.get(0); // need casting
Example with Generics
ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add("Hello");

String text = list.get(0); // no casting needed

Now the compiler already knows that the list contains String.

Generic Classes

We can create our own generic classes using type parameters.

public class Box<T> {
    private T value;

    public void set(T value) {
        this.value = value;
    }

    public T get() {
        return value;
    }
}

Here, T is a placeholder for any type.

Generic Methods

Generics can also be used in methods:

public <T> void print(T value) {
    System.out.println(value);
}
Bounded Generics

Sometimes we want to restrict the type:

public <T extends Number> void printNumber(T value) {
    System.out.println(value);
}

Now T can only be a subclass of Number.

Summary
Generics make code type-safe
remove the need for casting
allow writing reusable and flexible code
work with classes, methods, and collections
